":"Higham, Suffolk, England","Gazeley, Suffolk, England":"Gazeley, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England"},"en":{"1368–7 February 1409":"1368–7 February 1409","1368–1409":"1368–1409","1371–1383":"1371–1383","1372–1393":"1372–1393","1372–1448":"1372–1448","1398–1480":"1398–1480","1338–1404":"1338–1404","1340–1409":"1340–1409","1340":"1340","1372":"1372","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1393":"1393","1371":"1371","1480":"1480","24 May 1404":"24 May 1404","1404":"1404","1338":"1338","1448":"1448","1368":"1368","1398":"1398","about 1398":"about 1398","7 February 1409":"7 February 1409","about 1354":"about 1354","1409":"1409","23 May 1398":"23 May 1398","Higham, Suffolk, England":"Higham, Suffolk, England","Gazeley, Suffolk, England":"Gazeley, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Higham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the places called Higham (Lancashire, Yorkshire, Derbyshire, Leicestershire, Northamptonshire, Bedfordshire, Warwickshire, Essex, and Kent) or from Heigham in Norfolk. Most of the placenames derive from Old English <i>hēah</i> ‘high’ + <i>hām</i> ‘village, homestead’, though the Norfolk placename may come from Old English <i>hecg</i> ‘hedge’ or <i>hecc</i> ‘hatch, gate’ + <i>hām</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":14,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Higham II was born in 1368, his father, Thomas Highman I, was 30 and his mother, Mrs. Mawde Heigham, was 28. He married Alice Hune about 1398, in Higham, Suffolk, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 7 February 1409, in Higham, Suffolk, England, at the age of 41."},"et":{"1368–7 February 1409":"1368–7. veebruar 1409","1368–1409":"1368–1409","1371–1383":"1371–1383","1372–1393":"1372–1393","1372–1448":"1372–1448","1398–1480":"1398–1480","1338–1404":"1338–1404","1340–1409":"1340–1409","1340":"1340","1372":"1372","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1393":"1393","1371":"1371","1480":"1480","24 May 1404":"24. mai 1404","1404":"1404","1338":"1338","1448":"1448","1368":"1368","1398":"1398","about 1398":"umbes 1398","7 February 1409":"7. veebruar 1409","about 1354":"umbes 1354","1409":"1409","23 May 1398":"23. mai 1398","Higham, Suffolk, England":"Higham, Suffolk, England","Gazeley, Suffolk, England":"Gazeley, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1368–7 February 1409":"1368–7. helmikuuta 1409","1368–1409":"1368–1409","1371–1383":"1371–1383","1372–1393":"1372–1393","1372–1448":"1372–1448","1398–1480":"1398–1480","1338–1404":"1338–1404","1340–1409":"1340–1409","1340":"1340","1372":"1372","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1393":"1393","1371":"1371","1480":"1480","24 May 1404":"24. toukokuuta 1404","1404":"1404","1338":"1338","1448":"1448","1368":"1368","1398":"1398","about 1398":"noin 1398","7 February 1409":"7. helmikuuta 1409","about 1354":"noin 1354","1409":"1409","23 May 1398":"23. toukokuuta 1398","Higham